The Spanish healthcare system relies heavily on hiring Latin American doctors for cheap.

snippet.textDisplay:
Spain is a pioneer in preventive medicine.
Preventive medicine comprises four types of actions: The first focuses on health promotion, protection and chemoprophylaxis (administration of drugs to prevent diseases). The second, which is also called early diagnosis, screening, or screening, aims to detect and treat the disease in very early stages, so the chances of success are much greater and the cost of care much less. The third consists of the necessary actions to prevent complications and sequelae of an established disease. And the fourth focuses on the set of health activities that mitigate or avoid the consequences of unnecessary or excessive interventions of the health system.

snippet.textDisplay:
Yes, taking care of one's health is important, and doing things that put your health at risk (e.g. smoking) is just asking for trouble.
But it's also worth keeping in mind that many ailments can occur regardless of how well you look after yourself, for example genetic disorders, cancer, and of course unforeseeable accidents. It's not always someone's fault they are sick, and no one should have to pay excessive amounts of money for something they have no control over.

A problem with the rankings is, which data point you give more value. I have seen many rankings of healthcare systems and each time it was another country.
I have seen my country on top, The Netherlands, but in another survey, it was France, one time it was Brittain, Taiwan, Singapore, etc. And most of those surveys look at the same data points, like cost, accessibility, healthcare outcomes, average life expectancy, etc. However, the differences in those surveys are, how much value you give each data point.

The only country where all those surveys agree upon, the USA always somewhere on the bottom of those charts.....

snippet.textDisplay:
Hong Kong's health system has its up and down. 
Due to other factors, not everyone can afford the cheaper medical care compared to the US. High rent and low wages often prevent people to visit doctors. There are public non-hospital clinics, but do have long lines. Unless you're stay at home parent (which is rare) or an elderly, you usually don't have time to visit these clinics since you'll be working.
But many basic services and medication are cheap and no insurance required. 
If I have a cold in Hong Kong, I'll go see a doctor for a low price and they will give me some light medication, especially symptom reducing anti-histamines. If I have a cold in the US, I'll avoid the doctor because usually, they'll just say get some rest and have chicken noodle soup. 
Doctors in Hong Kong are more willing to give medication than US doctors, but more reluctant to prescribe long term medication. Ironically, the ease of giving out medication hasn't lead to abuse or dependency like the US, probably because most of the medication are weaker than the US. 
Cost are also kept down thanks to the avoidance of unnecessary medical procedures. An annual physical is considered unnecessary for people under 60s... I was laughed at when I requested a physical at age of 24. They still let me have a physical and it costed less than a Red Lobster dinner for two in the US. 
Because of the cheap basic doctor's visit, people are not as reluctant to go for a visit. If you happened to have a serious health issue, it'll probably get caught. 
ER in Hong Kong can get overwhelming if you're not dying, especially during flu season. Ambulance is free and if you're actually dying, they are pretty fast at fixing you up. 
Dental is also cheap. I can get a cleaning without insurance cheaper than a single Red Lobster dinner in the US.

snippet.textDisplay: @Kay Van Yes, propaganda. Those ”healthcare index” rankings usually base their analysis on facts that tilts everything in the favour government healthcare while leaving out incredibly essential facts and hence are very biased and I don’t trust them that easily. This is simply because the academia is so left-leaning in the Western world. Besides that, none of us Nordic countries(I am Finnish) could have anything close to the systems we have if it were not for the medical and technological innovation that comes primarily from the United States. We don’t develop any of that because there is no incentives here to innovate because of really high taxes and the discouraging of entrepreneurship. Furthermore the systems are unsustainable and will eventually fall like a house of cards since the government can’t keep loaning money forever and not pay back. That is also true of the United States as well. That is why the government everywhere must get out the way no matter how politically inconvenient that might be. People nowadays think free healthcare, free food, free housing, free education and so forth are ”human rights” and that list just keeps expanding. It’s nonsense and it might be 5 years or it might be 50 years until people realize that but it will come. And for the record, I am not praising the US healthcare system either, I think it is on the same road of destruction as we are.

snippet.textDisplay:
It seems to me that the majority of Americans believe that the whole world envies them and wants to live there. As i was growing up, we regularly heard reports on the news about mass shooting and other serious crimes in the US. I regularly heard my parents and grand parents say how awful it must be to live there. And even recently, we still hear reports of mass shootings. There are more murders in Washington DC in one month than there are in the UK for a whole year! As a country, it's true that the US is very wealthy. But I repeat.....as a country! The disparity between the wealthy and poor in the US is wider than any other country. The wealthy truly are wealthy, but there are far far more people living in absolute poverty! I regularly send money to friends of mine in NY state, as they struggle to survive. 
Our health service in the Uk does have problems, it's true, but it is still one of the best in the world. If I am ill, I don't have to worry about receiving hospital care. The same cannot be said about the US. Going into the hospital has resulted in many Americans going bankrupt. 
No wonder you all carry guns.....crime is so high there. What an awful country to live in!
